  "opinion": "As an 85-year-old retired man living in New York, I've seen a lot change over the years, from newspapers to this newfangled social media I dabble in for about an hour each day. Managing fake content on these platforms feels a bit like tending my garden—it requires patience, a keen eye, and a bit of old-fashioned common sense. With no formal education myself, though my parents were highly educated with master's and PhD degrees, I've learned to rely on my creative side and life experience to navigate things. Fake news and misleading posts pop up like weeds; they can spread fast and choke out the truth if you're not careful. My approach is simple: I don't take everything at face value. When I come across something suspicious, I pause and think it through, much like when I'm reading a novel and questioning the plot twists. I might check other sources or ask my children, who are more tech-savvy, for their take. Social media companies should do more to weed out this nonsense, but until then, it's on us users to be vigilant. I'm not one to argue much—my low agreeableness and extraversion mean I keep to myself—but I believe in fostering a respectful online space by ignoring or reporting fake content rather than engaging in fights. It's about protecting our community, just like I protect my garden from pests. In the end, dealing with fake content is about balance: enjoying the connections social media offers while staying grounded in reality, much like my agnostic views remind me to question and seek truth without blind faith.",
